They've got a veggie option (it may or may not be seasonal/rotating) and the shrimp po boy and the pork belly po boy are fantastic. If I'm going to grab something casual I'm the French Quarter this is where I always come.

I was here this past weekend for the 49ers invasion in NOLA.  Saw the reviews for this place so I wanted to try... especially the seared shrimp.  I've been to other local Po Boy shops trying their fried shrimp po boys, dressed and with the Leidenheimer bread (best bread).  When you get to the spot via GPS, you're like ... "where is it?" Location takes you to a bar (and yes, read location lol). Just walk in and it's towards the back.  RED greeted us as we approached the register and was very friendly.  She took our order and informed us it would take about 10 minutes. I believe Robert was the chef who cooked and prepared our meals.  OMG... has to be one of the best bites I've had! The shrimp were cooked perfectly, very tender and juicy. The combination of carrots, other veggies and the bread (their own fresh bread from another bakery) go really well with the shrimp. And I must say, coming from the Bay Area (San Jose) we have lots of places that prepare their sandwiches like Killer PoBoy. So if you're familiar with a banh mi, this is what the Killer Poboys sandwich best resembles. I would not say it's a po boy because of its Vietnamese similarities.  Keep in mind, I did have a few drinks before so I was hungry and it was dark inside so I don't have a good photo. Overall, Red and Robert did a great job and I really enjoyed the sandwich! Will definitely be back.

Hands down best po-boy I've ever had.  When I first got to New Orleans I tried some mom and pop restaurant for a po-boy. Was just bread, fried shrimp, lettuce and mayo. Took a bite and threw it away.  I was hesitant to try another po-boy, but watched a YouTube video about this place. It's a bit hard to find. Look up a bar called Erin Rose, walk passed the bar, and go to the back. I ordered the Glazed Pork Belly Po-Boy. AMAZE BALLS! Loved it. The flavors worked so well together. Pork was so tender and the coleslaw inside was to die for. I only meant to eat half of it, but ended up eating the whole thing.  Definitely try this place, you won't regret it.

By far the best Po'Boys I've had in my life. Do yourself  favor and come here. You won't regret it.  I got the Glazed Pork Belly Po'Boy, Gulf Shrimp Po'Boy, and the Beer Braised Beef Po'Boy. And I'll tell you, it was the most enjoyable gastronomic experience I've ever had as a stranger in a strange land. Glenn is actually a culinary genius and David, the barkeep, is gregarious in a way that hints to the fact that he stacked all of his stat points in charisma.  Food, atmosphere, and conversation; I heard there South had it all, but this place has it in spades.

This is the original location although “Killer” did open their own place over on Dauphine.  Think “out-of-the-box” PoBoys like Pork belly with rum ginger glaze called “Dark & Stormy”... or a Black beer beef debris. Their new place is cool, but there’s something about getting a funky PoBoy in the back of a bar that’s just... well... cooler.😎👍

Came here late one night on Mardi Gras weekend at the behest of a friend, and it did not disappoint. The business itself is located at the back of the bar, and apparently a separate entity from the bar itself. There's not much space to sit, there being one table that can sit about 6, a bar counter for a few people, and another counter for a few more. Overall, pretty small.  I had the shrimp poboy, which to be quite honest reminded me a lot of a Vietnamese banh mi. Had I been told that before, I might've been turned off from it (despite being a banh mi fan), but it actually worked out quite well for perhaps the same reason banh mi works well. The shrimp were grilled nicely, and the sandwich was on nice crunchy french will filled with carrots and daikon.  Definitely a good place to drop into for a late night bite after some good times on Bourbon St.

This bar is a must go to kinda dive place. It's a pretty small spot and nothing particularly special in drinks but the bartenders are nice and people here have a good vibe. It's not your typical bourbon street type of chaos bar. Additionally I'd say they have one of the top 3 shrimp po boys of Nola. It's Viet style stuffing with perfectly fresh cooked gulf shrimp. It's just definitely a place you should go! They are also cash only for food as an FYI

The service was good. It's a friendly dive bar if you want a po boy  just walking back room. You're likely to find a series of drunken young people hanging out up front smoking cigarettes. It's got a great youthful Vibe. All kinds of interesting murals and a neon-lit spaces featuring cigarette machine and other novelties not usually seen anywhere other than New Orleans.

Ate here for the first time this trip.  I have been looking for original po boy sandwiches with great flavor combinations and great bread. These guys did the trick. I got the “Dark & Stormy” Pork Belly Po Boy and it was soo good. The garlic aioli was the perfect addition to this sandwich. It is kind of hard to find and had to go through the bar to get to the restaurant, but it is worth looking for. I can't wait to try some of their other sandwiches on my next trip.

I give the Killer Poboys on Conti, the hidden gem located in the back of Erin Rose, 5 stars. The main hub on dauphine is 4 stars. I love the fact that Erin rose and Killer Poboys teamed up. This location gets the extra star for that collaboration and the cool back room vibe. It's so good I always forget to take a pic!!  I've had both the shrimp and the pork belly poboys. Which is better? It pretty much comes down to a coin flip. I first went on my first visit to Nola when I was on a cross country road trip.  Having never been to Nola, I was excited for my first authentic poboy. A friend recommended Johnnys poboys in the quarter, but in 2015 they were closed for some reason. My friend who I was traveling with then googled for the best poboy in the quarter and we saw we were near killer. What a happy accident.  I've now made sure to bring every new comer to New Orleans experience Killer Poboys and it's backroom charm on Conti st.

Interesting little place with the best poboys we had on our trip. You have to fight your way past what can very a crowded and narrow bar, through a little ante-room with an ATM, and finally into a small, square room, with a hatch for food ordering on one side, a small bar on another an done table. There's a fairly limited selection of poboys, but make no mistake, these are among the best there are to be in had in the French Quarter. We had a shrimp and a pork belly. Both absolutely delicious, served with a slaw on the sandwich that was outstanding. Coupled with one of the on-tap beers available at the bar, this was one of the best unexpected surprises on our trip. Definitely worth fighting to the back of the bar for.

Interesting take on po boys that is well worth a try. We ordered the Seared gulf shrimp po boy- basically a mix of banh mi (Vietnamese sand which and po boy. The sandwich comprised of a Vietnamese baguette and grilled shrimp mixed with pickled vegetables. Honestly, it was more like a banh mi. The flavors were excellent, but just not enough shrimp to pack a punch. Also, it's a po boy without the all important po boy bread!! For all of this, it was a steep $14 bucks! A banh mi is usually like around 5$. I really debated between 3-4 stars because while the sandwich was delicious, the cost did not match the expectation which was for a po boy, not a banh mi without enough shrimp. If you're on a po boy your as i was though, go ahead and give this place a shot. It's located inside the Erin rose bar in the back.

Went to New orleans to try this place out since it had so many reviews on Yelp.  This is actually connected to a bar, so it can be confusing if you've never been here before. It's called Erin something. My apologies that I do not recall the name of the bar.  Their area is very small in the back and you get lucky if you find seating back there. I ordered the Gulf Shrimp Poboy and oh my it was delicious. I thought it was cooked perfectly and the shrimp was a good size. The flavors blended with each other very well. It's even better with hot sauce in my opinion.  I would def come back here when I come back to New Orleans. I'm glad i was able to find this place on Yelp to try out.  My friends did get the meatloaf one and thought it was okay in their opinion. My friends don't like seafood, so they wouldn't have ordered the Shrimp poboy.
get the dark & stormy! incredible po-boy. if you could only have one po-boy in NOLA I would recommend it to be this one.
Po boys are mire like Vietnamese sandwiches (Bahn mi) but they are fresh and delicious, the beer is cheap, and the service is friendly!

Best po boys we had in NOLA! He had the pork belly and I had the shrimp po boys. Good thing we split both. While the pork belly is delicious, it's a lot of pork belly for one person! The flavors were outstanding! We will be back!
Delicious poboys. Have to go to the back of the bar to order. Very worth it.
Hidden away and a great find, poboys with a twist and very yummy
Ate at the new location on dauphine, fantastic just like the pop up location. Service was only exceeded by the quality of the food.
The shrimp bo poy is delicious
First poboy I had in new Orleans and after a couple it was my favorite.
These aren't traditional po-boys but they are a refreshing take on them. Be warned, it's at the back of the Erin Rose Bar and it's cash only.

Poboys are a flawed concept for a restaurant, people want a hearty meal, not a ton of bread and a tiny bit of shrimp. I get that America had a rough few years and you had to serve what ever you could to get by but that time has past.
Great food and low drink prices
Best in town! Not your usual poboy, created by Professional Chefs!
4 choices and nothing special about any of it. Will not be back or recommend.
Pork belly, you won't regret it.
The restaurant is located in the back of a bar. Best PO boys in the French quarter I was told. The roast beef meatloaf hit the spot. Cash only. Limited seating. Menu tiny and changes. Belly full.
This place is amazing. Fast, delicious, with killer condiments and a small but perfect menu (with a vegan option!).
The shrimp po boy and the pork po boys are good!
Good food
Wow, what a great little place. Delicious poboys!

Shrimp poboy was badly made. The shrimp was overcooked, old, chewy and left a bad after taste. The carrots was a little in the sour side. Though, the bread is pretty good. Since it is my first time eating here, I'll give them the benefit of the doubt and will call it a bad day. I'll try it again next time and let's see what happens. Did I mention I paid $15 for it...
Best po boys I've had.

Great poboys tucked in the back of my favorite bar in the French quarter The pork belly poboy was delicious but just a little sweet The shrimp poboy had a great flavor and the pickled veg was a great addition

I had sprained my ankle pretty bad to the point where I had been on crutches for the past three weeks.  I had planned my NOLA trip for a month, and I didn't want to cancel.  Because I couldn't walk far from the hotel, I was happy to find taht Killer Poboys was only a block away.  Enter the bar and go straight to the back room.  That's where you'll find them.  The menu is small, and delicious.  I got the pork belly and the sweet potato the next day.  My sister got the shrimp poboy twice.  The back room is very small, and there aren't a lot of places to sit.  I think you can eat in the bar, but there's a drink minimum.  If you can't find a place to sit and don't want to drink at that bar, best to just get the poboy to go.  I really liked the flavors, and I liked the banh mi influence.  The pork belly had a sweet glaze, and the sweet potato was both savory and sweet.  The lines get pretty long, so the wait can be awhile.  But it's worth it.
More reminiscent of a bahn mi than a traditional po boy. Pork belly and shrimp were very good.

Hidden in the back of the Erin Rose, this little shop is putting their own spin on poboys.  The poboys are a little dressed up and more for savoring, but they'll hit the spot on a late night food run.  Be prepared to wait though... you might as well grab a drink while you're in the Erin Rose.
Fantastic. Worth the hype. 10 stars in my book. Shrimp was perfect. Next time I'm going for the pork belly.

First timer in the French Quarter was looking for the best PO-boy experience.  This place did not disappoint. The shrimp was fantastic. Paired with some jalapeño chips and a couple cheap beers. FANTASTIC. Would recommend, will come back again. Great staff. IS cash only. Don't pass it up!

Split a sweet potato Po boy with my friend who got the meatloaf and we couldn't really taste a difference between the two. Hot sauces were good but absolutely necessary on the otherwise bland sandwiches. Beer was cheap, cook was friendly.  Maybe an off night, maybe my expectations were too high, I'm not sure but I was unimpressed.
Great cheap drinks at the bar and the poboys were fantastic. Will definitely be recommending this place!
If you don't travel here from faraway lands to eat the Jameson grilled cheese, you are an idiot.
Super delish and original po boys in a great divey bar!
Cool little place in the back of the bar , make sure you bring cash.  Didn't care for the pork belly, it was a little tough.  But the Shrimp was amazing !
a little place inside a bar. wonderful food!
Great food, staff was awesome.
Delish! No sign. Look for the Erin Rose Irish bar; the po-boy place is in back.
Awesome shrimp and pork poboys in an undescript hole in the wall place

Great bread, meatloaf, eggplant, pork belly, shrimp-all the poboys of the day.  Great flavors!  Every one a winner!  5 stars for food and the speed of delivery,  negative 5 stars for the smoking from the bar.  But it IS in the back of a bar after all.
Awesome po'boys!
Such Finesse! Very tasty indeed.  The most delicious po boys in the quarter, come with friends and you will be so happy!
